# Issue #861 — non-tail recursive raw-scalar call must not box/unbox per
# call. `fib` is a UFn with a raw `Int` param + raw `Int` return, and its
# body combines TWO non-tail call results with `+` (the case a self-tail
# loop never hits). Before the fix, the native backend re-boxed each call
# result (`kaix_int`) and the consuming `+` unbox-borrowed it back
# (`kaix_int_field`) — one box + one unbox per recursive call, ~8× over the
# C-direct oracle on the fib call tree.
#
# The fix makes the call result land in a RAW register (`lower_direct_call`
# binds the callee's return slot), the args pass raw (no `int.box` at the
# callee boundary), and the raw `if`-join carries the `i64` straight to the
# raw `ret` — so the whole `fib` body is native `add`/`sub`/`cmp` that O2
# amplifies to C parity. The KIR shows `.tN: i64 = fib(...)` and a single
# `i+` over two i64 registers, with NO `int.box`/`int.unbox` in the loop.
#
# The harness diffs native stdout + exit vs the C-direct oracle, guarding
# correctness of the raw call ABI + raw `if`-join. RC: a raw call result and
# a raw join carry no refcount; perceus skips them (the nodes are MUnboxed),
# so no double-free — verified with KAI_TRACE_RC balanced over this shape.
fn fib(n: Int) : Int =
  if n < 2 { n }
  else { fib(n - 1) + fib(n - 2) }

fn main() : Unit / Stdout = {
  Stdout.print("#{fib(20)}")
}
